How the prices of the voyages evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were in Czechoslovakia only 5 travel agencies of state: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
The travel agencies at that time especially proposed voyages in the countries of the socialist block, because the voyages to the west were very limited.
The Czech tourists travelled for the vacancies to East Germany, Soviet Union (Sotchi, the Crimea and Black Sea), in Bulgaria, Romania (both at sea Noire) and in Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period of 1962 to 1972 when it was authorized to travel to Yugoslavia then the mode started to have an inclination for the west and the voyages towards Yugoslavia were very limited for the Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist time was that it nétait not authorized for the citizens of the socialist block (also for the Czechoslovakian ones) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the Tchécoslovaque citizen wanted to travel individually for example to Poland or Soviet Union it needed an invitation letter if not the individual voyage was not authorized.
The travel agencies at that time however offered also voyages to the West it was necessary to make the tail all the night with a bag of bed or to have a “good knowledge " within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not gained yet.
The agreement for the currencies which was the condition to travel to the west was refused with “politically incorrect " people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovakian currency was not however exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currencies (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs generally spent their vacancies in the country where there were consequently many country cottage and country houses which the Czechs bought and this practice lasts until now.
The voyages of the Czechs since knew since 1989 a great revolution.
Although until 1989 the vacancies in East Germany and Bulgaria were to the maximum, the Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million days of vacancies in the countries of the whole world.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today it is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go because left Yugoslavia of the time freely until 1989.
The removal of the visas in the Nineties of last century in the adjoining countries of the west caused an enormous wave of visits of short time especially in Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakian ones could not travel for a long time by plane to the west that each one wanted to see at least a moment.
For example in Paris the organizations of voyages made sleep the Czechs in tents in the parks because our incomes did not enable us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech voyage was at that time to carry with oneself its own food preserves, sausage, etc… to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which allowed our tourists finally after tens of years of freely being able to buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wages increased what caused around the year 1997 another important moment.
Thanks to an increasing demand for the voyages the travel agencies started to since 1997 prepare turns with connections by air charters which thanks to contracts formidably reduced the costs compared to what there was front.
At the end of the Nineties of last century the Czechs had connections without visas with practically most developed countries of the whole world except for HAVE which later facilitated our voyages.
Another interesting moment in the history of tourism post-revolution, when the first air charter towards an exotic country was prepared, Thailand, starting from the Czech Republic.
For this year as each year of the direct air charters have taken along Czech tourists in the remote hot countries\; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations starting from the Czech Republic.
It is more than 100000 Czechs who visit the exotic countries each year!
Still an interesting moment during this time which symbolizes our development post-revolution arrived in 2008.
on November 17th, 2008 HAVE the visas for the Czech tourists removed and made it possible our country to completely line up in the group of the developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in the history passed more half of their vacancies abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time still in the history spent more than 15,000 crowns per anybody for vacancies abroad including the additional loads. Crowns by anybody.
