The asphalt of the UNAM would avoid blackcurrants
Rafael Herrera, researcher of Faculté of Chemistry of the UNAM, develops the asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with a better output, independently of the environmental conditions and temperature
If announce them that the paving stone were solved, it would not be necessary any more to repair approximately 200 thousand blackcurrants each season of rain in the Metropolitan Zone of Valle of Mexico City, informs Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of Faculté of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, which ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous paving stone is adequate, the blackcurrants could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During its conference a technological opinion on blackcurrants, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, it announced that the laboratory for which it is responsible develops the asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture having characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with a larger mechanical resistance, so much with the high ones like low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this kind of modified asphalts could be used in places in which the climate is extremely hot, like certain cities of the north of the country, to improve the output, and consequently, the formation of blackcurrants.
He explained why asphalt, the heavier share of oil, is a set of molecule, hydrocarbon molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a molecular weight low, called malthenes, which together give to the paving stone its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists of the fact that at high temperatures, of almost 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, with 120 degrees c its viscosity is very large and to 50 degrees c it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, asphalt becomes breakable, he added.
That means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to the environmental conditions and of temperature, informs the specialist in chemical engineering.
The researcher of the FQ observed that the streets of Ciudad of Mexico City in their majority were covered by a flexible paving stone, composed of six layers of materials, whose three last imply asphalt.
Between the surface layers the layer of asphalt is, formed by small stones bathed out of asphalt and compacted later on.
Each small stone which forms the layer, announced it, is bathed year asphalts.
When the vehicles pass there while generating efforts, this one allows that the forces are propagated very well in the paving stone.
If there were modified asphalt, those would be propagated better, opinât the chemical ingénier.
On the layer of asphalt, he says, one puts a last layer called course wearing, made out of fine stone, i.e., sand which is also bathed out of asphalt.
As this one is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the layer of asphalt and provide adherence in the street.
Being the part of the paving stone which receives and distributes the efforts, the wearing course also requires that this one have an adequate thickness and the material of which it is made must be neat.
The climate, especially moisture and the temperature variations, are also a factor very important to consider, especially water, he says, because those affect considerably the output of the layer of asphalt.
When the ground is wet, water is spread inside the layer is it is difficult that this one left, which softened all the layers of the paving stone and consequently causes blackcurrants.
In the lawsuit of formation of a blackcurrant, he says, the first which trowel is the film of bearing and only later on is affected the layer of asphalt, but the damage does not take place immediately, but these is a process which must be neat with the first signals with adequate programs of maintenance.
The member of the National System of the Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another significant factor for the blackcurrant formation and consequently the thickness of each layer of the paving stone must be always related to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, to avoid the frequent blackcurrant formation.
Rafael Herrera informed that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, the bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and make it possible to easily repair blackcurrants and without having to use high temperatures.
