On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that “900000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country including nearly 2 million immigrant workers”, and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France “cannot accommodate all the misery of the world in 1990”.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on the left like on the right.
