This idea of immigration like a load, a problem, is perhaps paying electorally\; but it is economically very expensive.
As point out it the economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron in a recent work synthesizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Future Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our, May 2011, Princeton University Close, 352 pp.), there exists a broad consensus among the specialists on the positive impact in the migratory flux on the economic growth, the wages and employment in the countries which receive immigrants.
To restrict immigration weakens the growth and harms employment.
Fears with respect to the impact of the migrants are founded on the idea that those are likely to replace the national workers, particularly the qualified little, putting pressure downwards on their wages.
But the experiment shows that, actually, the immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes to the national employees, exerting essentially trades in sectors in shortage of employment.
The little qualified immigrants work in sectors which do not attract the national employees, and the most qualified in dynamic sectors in which the formation does not follow the job offer.
A positive effect on the wages
In the same way that a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country which knows a shortage of anesthetists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make that the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on the wages and the use of the nationals.
Giovanni Peri thus calculated that a rise of 1% of the migratory flux involves an increase ranging between 0.6 and 0.9% of the real wages in the long run.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by the immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and the economic growth (strong proportion of immigrants naturalized among the Nobel Prize American\; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were rested by immigrants).
The migrants are also net contributors of the social systems, on average to a total value of 1% of the total budget in the European countries.
The Worldwide organization of work estimates for example that, in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the 30 years age will make a clear contribution (receipts minus expenditure) of 150000 euros to the public budgets on average on the whole of his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wished, at the beginning of mandate, outward journey to seek the missing points of growth “with the teeth”.
The teeth in question, while being used to dissuade the immigrants, had the exact adverse effect.
