Why the unemployment rate of the handicapped workers remain does so high?
Approximately 19% of the handicapped people are in search of a work.
The 15th week for the employment of the handicapped people opens today.
In spite of a voluntarist public policy installation in 2005, the unemployment rate of the handicapped people is still twice higher than the average: 19%, against 9% for the whole of the population.
Discouraging?
“Not, underlines Eric Blanchet, chief executive officer of Adapt, the association which organizes the week for the employment of the handicapped people. ”
“Good progresses for fifteen years have been considerable. ”
“At the time, unemployment rate was not two but three times higher. ”
“It still enormously remains nevertheless to make. ”
It should be said that for the handicapped unemployed, the obstacles remain numerous before reaching employment.
They are rather old: 37% have more than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a qualification level relatively low: 80% do not have the vat and on the 2.3 million students of higher education, 10,000 only are handicapped.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the handicapped people, against 38% on average.
In short, as many criteria which complicate the return to employment singularly, and which “constitute the node of the problem”, according to Christian Grapin, chief executive officer of Springboard, an association created to help the companies in 1992 to recruit handicapped workers.
Here are for the objective brakes.
Remain the unvoiced comment, mentalities which evolve, certainly, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by association IMS-To undertake for the City indicated that the questioned managers have “a low level of knowledge of the handicap”, with a “over-representation of the people in wheelchair, defective psychic the or intellectual ones”.
Result, the private companies of more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the goal of use of 6% of handicapped workers, fixed in a law of… 1987.
The last known figures, which go back to 2008, mention a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%”, indicates Pierre Blanc, chief executive officer of Agefiph, the organism in charge to collect the contributions of the companies which do not comply with this law.
The proof: the number of “taxed” establishments, just like the paid amounts, fell between 2007 and 2011, passing 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The law of 2005, which increased the contributions, created a strong pressure on the companies, explains Pierre Blanc. ”
“But this improvement translates also a true awakening, in particular in the great groups. ”
According to the ministry for employment, only 59% of the establishments from 20 to 49 employees employ handicapped workers, against 82% of the companies from 100 to 199 employees.
